So I need to figure out what motivates employees. This seems like a pretty broad topic, but I'll try to break it down. First off, I should probably understand what motivation means in this context. Motivation, I think, is about what drives employees to work hard, be productive, and stay committed to their jobs. It's about what makes them want to come to work every day and give their best.

I recall that there are different theories about motivation in psychology and management. There's Maslow's hierarchy of needs, Herzberg's two-factor theory, and maybe others like expectancy theory or reinforcement theory. Maybe I should look into these theories to get a better grasp of what motivates people at work.

Let me start with Maslow's hierarchy of needs. Maslow proposed that humans have a hierarchy of needs, from basic physiological needs like food and shelter, up to higher needs like belonging, esteem, and self-actualization. In the context of work, this could mean that employees need to have their basic needs met before they can focus on higher-level needs like achievement and fulfillment.

